In

method
based
on
ultra
performance
liquid
chromatography
tandem
mass
spectrometry
(UPLC-MS/MS)
technique
for

of
plasma
selexipag

ACT-333679

in
rats
was

and

The

of

ACT-333679
and
the
internal
standard
(IS,
diazepam)
was
accomplished
using
an
Acquity
BEH
C18
(2.1
mm
×
50
mm,
1.7
␮m)

The

phase
was
consisted
of
acetonitrile
(solution
A)
and
0.1
%

acid
in
water
(solution
B)

procedure
with
a
ﬂow

of
0.40

The

of
the
analytes
and
IS
was
explored
using
a
XEVO
TQ-S
triple
quadrupole
tandem
mass
spectrometer,
which
was
comprised
with
electrospray
ionization
(ESI)

Selected

(MRM)

was
employed
to
detect
the

ion
transitions
as
follows:
m/z
497.4
→
302.2
for
selexipag,
m/z
420.1
→
378.2
for
ACT-333679,
and
m/z
285.0
→
154.0
for
diazepam
(IS),
respec-
tively.
The
new

method
showed
good

respectively
at
the

curve
range
of
0.05−50
ng/mL
for

and
0.05−250
ng/mL
for

The

inter-day
of
accu-
racy
and

were
all
within
the
acceptable
limits
in
the

method,
and
the
results
of
recovery
and
matrix

were
also
met
the

The

developed

assay
was
forward
successfully
used
to
describe
the
pharmacokinetic
proﬁles
of
selexipag
and
ACT-333679
in
rats
after
oral

with
6.0
mg/kg
selexipag.

1.
Introduction
Pulmonary
arterial
hypertension
(PAH)
is
an
intractable
and
complicated
disease
that
can
threaten
life,
which
could
increase
the
resistance
of
pulmonary
blood
vessels
and
then
evelate
the
pressure
of
pulmonary
artery,
and
result
in
the
right
heart
failure
and
death
ultimately
[1,2].
Selexipag
(Fig.
1A),
as
the
long-acting,
selective
and
ﬁrst
orally
active
nonprostanoid
prostacyclin
(IP)
receptor
agonist,
targets
the
prostacyclin
pathway,
and
it
is
cur-
rently
received
its
approval
for
the
clinical
treatment
of
PAH
[3–5].
ACT-333679
(Fig.
1B),
as
the
active
metabolite
of
selexi-
pag,
is
yielded
by
carboxylesterases
from
the
hydrolysis
reaction
in
the
human
liver
[5].
It
turned
out
that
both

and

However,

2.
Experimental
2.1.
Chemicals
and
reagent
Both
selexipag
and
ACT-333679
were
offered
from
Beijing
sun-
ﬂower
and
technology
development
CO.,
LTD
(Beijing,
China),
and
the
purity
of
each
substance
was
>98
%.
Diazepam
(purity
>98
%)
was
provided
by
Sigma
(St.
Louis,
MO,
USA),
and
was
selected
as
the
internal
standard
(IS)
in
this
experiment.
Acetonitrile
and
methanol
were
LC
grade
and
were
provided
by
Merck
Company
(Darmstadt,
Germany).
A
Milli
Q
system
(Millipore,
Bedford,
USA)
was
employed
to
prepare
the
HPLC
grade
water.
2.2.
Instrumentation
and
analytical
conditions
The
UPLC-MS/MS
system
(Waters
Corp.,
Milford,
MA,
USA)
used
for
analysis
in
this
experiment
was
comprised
of
the
Acquity
UPLC
H-Class
system
and
a
XEVO
TQ-S
triple
quadrupole
mass
spectrom-
eter
equipped
with
an
electrospray
ionization
(ESI)
source.
The
chromatographic
separation
of
the
analytes
and
IS
was
ﬁnished
on
an
Acquity
BEH
C18
column
(2.1
mm
×
50
mm,
1.7
␮m)
set
at
40 ◦C,
with
a
0.40
mL/min
ﬂow
rate
and
a
2.0
␮L
injection
volume
in
the
linear
gradient
elution
program.
The
mobile
phase
contained
ace-
tonitrile
(solvent
A)
and
water
with
0.1
%
formic
acid
(solvent
B)
for
the
separation
of
the
analytes
and
IS,
and
was
employed
within
3.0
min
for
an
entire
run
time
as
follows:
solvent
A
was
kept
at
10
%
for
0.5
min,
linearly
increased
from
10
%
to
90
%
in
the
following
0.5
min,
kept
at
90
%
for
1.0
min,
then
decreased
to
10
%
in
0.1
min
and
kept
stably
at
10
%
for
0.9
min.
Selected
multiple
reaction
monitoring
(MRM)
was
conducted
for
the
quantiﬁcation
analysis
in
the
mass
analyzers,
with
the
precursor-to-product
ion
transitions
of
m/z
497.4
→
302.2
for
selex-
ipag,
m/z
420.1
→
378.2
for
ACT-333679,
and
m/z
285.0
→
154.0
for
IS,
respectively.
The
cone
voltage
and
collision
energy
were
30
V
and
20
eV
for
both
selexipag
and
ACT-333679,
and
were
10
V
and
30
eV
for
IS,
respectively.
The
general
MS
parameters
were
optimized
as
follows:
desolvation
temperature
600 ◦C,
capillary
voltage
2.0
kV,
cone
gas
150
L/h,
desolvation
gas
1000
L/h,
collision
gas
0.15
mL/min.
The
software
Masslynx
4.1
(Waters
Corp.,
Milford,
MA,
USA)
was
selected
for
sample
quantitation,
data
analysis
and
also
instrument
control.

to

0.05,
0.1,
0.5,
1.0,
5,
10,
20,
50
ng/mL
for

and
0.05,
0.1,
0.5,
1.0,
5,
10,
50,
250
ng/mL
for
ACT-333679,
respec-
tively.
Similarly,
the
lower
limit
of
quantiﬁcation
(LLOQ),
low
(LQC),

2.4.
Sample
processing
To
each
100
␮L
of
plasma
sample,
300
␮L
acetonitrile
mixture
with
IS
at
a
concentration
of
10
ng/mL
was

in

to
pre-
cipitate
the
protein
from
plasma
samples
in
a
1.5

The

were
shaked
and
vortexed
for
1.0

and
then
immedi-

for
10

at

The

was
transferred
into
a
clean
and
new

and
only
2
␮L

was
selected
to
inject
into
the
UPLC-MS/MS
system
for
further
analysis.
2.5.
Method
validation
The
bioanalytical
method
by
UPLC-MS/MS
was
established
and
validated
before
it
was
put
to
determine
the
plasma
concentrations
of
the
analytes
in
rats,
by
assessing
the
selectivity,
carry-over
effect,
LLOQ,
linearity,
accuracy
and
precision,
recovery,
matrix
effect,
dilution
integrity,
and
stability
in
accordance
with
the
guidelines
of
Bioanalytical
Method
Validation
by
the
US
FDA
[11].
2.5.1.
Selectivity
and
carry-over
The
comparisons
of
the
typical
chromatograms
of
blank
plasma
samples
obtained
from
six
different
batches
of
rats,
blank
plasma
samples
spiked
with
standards
at
LLOQ
level
and
IS,
and
real
plasma
samples
collected
from
pharmacokinetic
study
in
rats
at
0.33
h
after
oral
administration
of
selexipag
at
a
dose
of
6.0
mg/kg
were
examined
to
evaluate
the
selectivity
in
this
method.
To
assess
the
carry-over
of
our
method,
we
injected
the
highest
calibration
stan-
dard
(n
=
5)
and
IS
before
the
injection
of
a
blank
sample
for
5
times.
Carry-over
in
the
drug-free
plasma
sample
had
to
be
<20
%
for
the
LLOQ
of
each
analyte
and
<5
%
for
IS.
2.5.2.
Linearity
of
calibration
curve
and
LLOQ
In
the
range
of
0.05–50
ng/mL
for
selexipag
and
0.05–250
ng/mL
for
ACT-333679
in
rat
plasma,
the
calibration
curves
of
each
analyte
at
the
corresponding
eight
concentration
levels
were
processed
in
duplicate
and
detected
by
our
developed
UPLC-MS/MS
method
in
three
consecutive
runs.
The
linearity
of
the
method
with
a
weight-
ing
(1/x2)
factor
was
evaluated
by
plotting
the
measured
peak
area
ratios
(each
analyte/IS
as
Y)
vs
the
corresponding
spiked
concen-
tration
(X)
of
each
analyte.
LLOQ
was
assessed
and
deﬁned
as
the
sensitivity
in
this
method.
LLOQ
should
yield
a
signal
of
at
least
ﬁve
times
that
of
the
blank
signal,
and
peak
of
IS
should
be
at
least
twenty
times
that
of
the
blank
signal.
2.5.3.
Accuracy
and
precision
LLOQ,
LQC,
MQC
and
HQC
samples
for
6
replicates
in
rat
plasma
were
operated
and
evaluated
on
three
consecutive
days
to
calcu-
late
the
intra-
and
inter-day
accuracy
and
precision.
All
the
results
of
this
part
experiment
were
evaluated
from
the
standard
curve
made
on
the
same
day.
Relative
error
(RE%)
and
relative
standard
deviation
(RSD%)
was
used
to
describe
the
accuracy
and
precision,
respectively.
Precision
for
QC
samples
should
be
less
than
15
%,
whereas
accuracy
should
lie
within
±
15
%
of
nominal
value,
and
within
±20
%
for
LLOQ
samples.
2.5.4.
Matrix
effect,
extraction
recovery
and
dilution
integrity
Three
different
processed
QC
samples
(LQC,
MQC
and
HQC)
were
obtained
and
used
to
evaluate
the
extraction
recovery
and
matrix
effect
of
selexipag
and
ACT-333679
in
this
study.
The
comparison
of
the
peak
areas
of
samples
extracted
from
plasma
(A),
post-
extracted
blank
plasma
spiked
samples
(B),
and
the
corresponding
pure
reference
standard
solutions
(C)
were
done,
where
A/B
was
deﬁne
as
the
extraction
recovery
and
B/C
was
considered
as
the
matrix
effect,
respectively.
Dilution
integrity
ensures
that
the
dilu-
tion
of
a
sample
with
a
concentration
higher
than
the
ULOQ
will
result
in
an
accurate
quantiﬁcation.
Six
10-fold
HQC
samples
were
diluted
10-fold
and
analyzed.
2.5.5.
Stability
The
stability
of
each
analyte
in
rat
plasma
were
investigated
and
validated
using
LQC,
MQC
and
HQC
samples
(n
=
5)
under
various
conditions,
including
auto-sampler,
short-term,
long-term
storage
and
three
complete
freeze/thaw
cycles.
For
each
analyte
at
the
corresponding
concentration,
the
stability
of
auto-sampler
storage
was
measured
by
determing
the
concentrations
of
post-
extraction
samples
after
being
placed
at
the
auto-sampler
for
6
h
at
10 ◦C
prior
to
analysis.
In
addition,
the
stability
of
short-term
and
long-term
storage
was
evaluated
after
being
placed
at
room
temperature
for
4
h
and
at
−20 ◦C
for
30
days,
respectively.
More-
over,
the
stability
of
freeze/thaw
experiment
was
detected
after
3
complete
freeze/thaw
cycles,
by
thawing
at
room
temperature
for
2−3
h
and
then
refreezing
at
−20 ◦C
for
12−24
h.
The
analytes
were
regarded
as
stable
when
the
calculated
concentration
was
within
±
15
%
of
the
nominal
concentration.
2.6.
Pharmacokinetic
study
The
novel
validated
bioanalytical
method
based
on
UPLC-
MS/MS
was
conducted
to
analysis
the
plasma
concentration
and
pharmacokinetic
study
of
selexipag
and
ACT-333679
after
a
single
oral
administration
of
selexipag
at
the
dose
of
6.0
mg/kg.
8
healthy
male
Sprague-Dawley
(SD)
rats
(body
weight
200
±
20
g)
were
provided
by
Laboratory
Animal
Center
of
Wenzhou
Medical
Univer-
sity
(Wenzhou,
China).
The
ethical
approval
for
the
experimental
protocols
and
procedures
were
achieved
from
Wenzhou
Medical
University
Animal
Care
and
Use
Committee
according
to
the
regu-
lations
deﬁned
by
National
Institutes
of
Health
(NIH)
Guidelines
for
Laboratory
Animal
Care.
All
the
rats
were
fasted
for
more
than
12
h
before
gavage,
while
water
was
freely
supplied.
Following
a
single
oral
administration
of
6.0
mg/kg
selexipag,
we
obtained
approx-
imately
0.3
mL
of
blood
samples
through
the
tail
veins
of
rats
at
each
of
the
following
time
points:
pre-dosing,
0.33,
0.67,
1,
1.5,
2,
3,
4,
6,
8,
12,
24
and
36
h
post-dosing.
All
the
collected
blood
samples
were
transferred
into
heparin-containing
tubes,
and
then
centrifugated
at
4000
g
for
10
min.
After
the
centrifugation,
100
␮L
plasma
was
separated
and
obtained,
1.0
M
hydrochloric
acid
was
added
(10
%
plasma
volume),
and
then
they
were
placed
at
−20
◦C
freezer
until
further
bioanalysis.
Following
the
quantiﬁcation
of
each
analyte
concentration,
the
main
pharmacokinetic
parame-
ters
in
this
study
for
selexipag
and
ACT-333679
were
accomplished
by
the
Drug
and
Statistics
(DAS)
2.0
software
(Shanghai
Univer-
sity
of
Traditional
Chinese
Medicine,
China)
in
non-compartmental
approach
from
the
rats.

ﬂow

in
ﬁnally.
For

Based

ﬁndings,

between

Therefore,

when

Finally,
10

to

of
the
acylglucuronide
of
ACT-333679
back
to
ACT-333679
in

as

[7].
3.2.

3.2.1.

The

In

present

the
concentration

6

of
